Data Exploration

#See if there is linear trend along the time line
plot(bluestem_0$Sales)

## Here timeindex only covers the operating dates. While tx covers all 7 days in a week.
timeindex <- c(1,3,4,5,6)
temp <- 6
for (lp in 6:249){
  if (bluestem_0$Saturday[lp]==1){
    temp <- temp+7
    timeindex[lp] <- temp
  }
  else if (bluestem_0$Sunday[lp]==1){
    timeindex[lp] <- timeindex[lp-1]+1
  }
  else if (bluestem_0$Monday[lp]==1){
    timeindex[lp] <- temp +2
  }
  else if (bluestem_0$Tuesday[lp]==1){
    timeindex[lp] <- temp +3
  }
  else if (bluestem_0$Wednesday[lp]==1){
    timeindex[lp] <- temp +4
  }
  else if (bluestem_0$Thursday[lp]==1){
    timeindex[lp] <- temp +5
  }
  else if (bluestem_0$Friday[lp]==1){
    timeindex[lp] <- temp +6
  }
}

bluestem_0$timeindex <- timeindex 

fit0 <- lm(bluestem_0$Sales ~ timeindex,data=bluestem_0)
summary(fit0)

Comparison

Model assumptions:
The additive model is much better in terms of R-square and residual plots. The multiplicative model using log(De-seasonalized Sales) is better than the one directly using De-seasonalized Sales.
Business perspective:
The multiplicative model is better than the additive model. The additive model assumes that promotions have same boost effect on all weekdays, which is not the case. Promotional events should have better results with larger customer traffic. This is better addressed by the multiplicative model.
